2 Introduction

This report uses the GREEN Grid project (Stephenson et al. 2017) research data to analyse a variety of residential household appliances and their contribution to peak demand under several scenarios.

3 Data

The NZ GREEN Grid household electricity demand study recruited a sample of c 40 households in each of two regions of New Zealand (Stephenson et al. 2017). The first sample was recruited in early 2014 and the second in early 2015. Research data includes:

  • 1 minute electricity power (W) data was collected for each dwelling circuit using GridSpy monitors on each power circuit (and the incoming power). The power values represent mean(W) over the minute preceding the observation timestamp;
  • Dwelling & appliance surveys;
  • Occupant time-use diaries (focused on energy use).

The data collection was supported by the New Zealand Ministry of Business, Innovation and Employment (MBIE) through the Renewable Energy and the Smart Grid (GREEN Grid) grant (Contract ID: UOCX1203).

## Date in ISO8601 format; converting timezone from UTC to "Pacific/Auckland".

4 Peak Contribution

In this section we use the GREEN Grid residential sample to estimate the contribution of each appliance to peak demand. For this analysis we use demand data averaged over 30 minute intervals. We consider three different definitions of peak demand:

  • Sample winter evenings 17:00 - 21:00. In this case we:
    • find the maximum half-hour demand for each household during the defined peak period
    • calculate the percentage contribution of each separately identifiable load type (lighting, hot water, heat pump, oven) in that half hour.
  • Regional/network peak. In this case we:
    • find the 100 maximum regional network (GXP) peak half hours
    • calculate the mean contribution of each identifiable load to mean total load across all households in that region across these 100 half-hours
  • Sample co-incident peak. In this case we:
    • find the half-hour across the sample which has the highest total combined demand
    • calculate mean contribution of each identifiable load to mean total load across all households in this half-hour

To do this last part we classify the circuit labels according to the load types mentioned above (see Table ?? in the Data Annex).

4.1 Winter (June - August) evenings 17:00 21:00

In this section we select the peak-period half hours for all households for the winter evening period and then locate the half-hour which had the maximum total load for that dwelling.

In this data extract, NaN indicates that no circuit data was obtained for this dwelling in this specific time period. We also calculate the proportionate contribution of each identifiable load to the total load. 4.2 Region/network coincident peak

In this section we focus on the contribution of these identifiable loads to regional peak demand. Most of the households in our data set were in the Hawkes Bay and Taranaki region, so we focus on these regions by separating the sample into the Hawkes Bay and Taranaki sub-samples.

22 houses are based in Taranaki and 20 houses in Hawkes Bay. Within the house sample in Taranaki, 31% of the houses have heat pumps installed, 45% hot water cylinders, and 27% other heat sources. In contrast, the Hawkes Bay sub-sample comprises of 90% heat pumps, 90% hot water cylinder, and 36% other heat sources.

e.g.see https://cfsotago.github.io/GREENGridData/householdAttributeProcessingReport_v1.0.html#51_main_heat_source

To determine the timing of the matching regional peaks, data on regional demand for the Hawkes Bay and Taranaki Grid Exit Point (GXP) was obtained from the Electricity Authority and for each GXP, the timestamps of the 100 half hours with the highest demand were identified. We then extracted the power demand of each dwelling in each of the two regions during these 100 half hours for analysis.

4.3 Sample coincident peak

In this section the sum of half-hourly demand over all dwellings in the the GREENGrid sample is used to define peak demand. We define the peak as the 20 half hours with the highest total half-hourly demand summed across all dwellings, which we refer to as the sample coincident peak. This is in contrast to section 4.1 where peak demand was predefined as the time between 17:00 and 21:00 in winter and section 4.2 where peak demand was predefined as the 100 half hours with the largest demand based on regional GXP data.

Table 4.4 identifies the half hours of highest overall demand in 2015 using the sum of the half-hourly mean power values (summeanPowerW). As we can see the number of dwellings contributing to this grand sum is between 31 and 33 and the table is sorted in descending order of the mean total power across all contributing dwellings. Clearly we would expect summed values with more contributing dwellings to be higher and so we control for missing dwellings by sorting by and using the mean total power (last column) as our indicator. The complete data table is saved as Extracted winter peak load half-hours in descending order for 2015 and is supplied with the report.

Figure 4.7 shows the mean contribution of each identifiable load for the sample for one of the identified peak half hours ( 2015-06-28 at 18:00:00). The results show that Hot Water contributes the most, followed by Heat Pumps and Lighting. The plot also shows that much power was drawn from circuits other than the identified ones (summarized in Others). Figure 4.8 shows the associated percentage contribution. Since the chosen half-hour is on the 2015-06-28 at 18:00:00 (winter) Heat Pump and Lighting demand are clearly contributing to peak demand, however, Hot Water is the circuit contributing the most.

Again, these results should be viewed with some caution due to the non-representative nature of the GREEN Grid sample. While they represent the sample co-incident peak contributions, we cannot assume that this is representative of all New Zealand dwellings.

5 Annual Contribution

This section presents annual and seasonal energy consumption (in kWh) for each identifiable load. This analysis considers the year 2015. Figure 5.1 shows the annual total energy consumption (in kWh) for the identifiable loads in a box and whisker plot to show the central distribution and also outliers. Hot Water consumes the most energy per year with a pronounced variation between houses. Lighting, Heat Pump, and Oven follow. Not further specified circuits are summarised in Others but this group clearly drives large inter-household variation.

Figure 5.1: Box and whisker plot of annual energy consumption (per house) of each identifiable load for 2015

Figure 5.2 conceals the significant variation in demand by the various appliances. In particular it conceals the differences between seasons. Figure 5.2 shows the distribution in seasonal energy consumption in kWh across all houses for Hot Water in 2015 using a density plot. Results show that most energy consumption of Hot Water is in winter, followed by spring and autumn. Energy consumption for hot water in summer is substantially lower with a distinctively different pattern to both the spring/autumn seasons and winter.

Figure 5.2: Distribution of easonal energy consumption for Hot Water for all houses for 2015

In contrast, Figure 5.3 presents the seasonal energy consumption for Heat Pumps and considers each dwelling and season. As expected, most energy consumption is in winter. In summer, total energy consumption is mostly 0 (appliance is turned off). Only a few observatons registered energy consumption in summer (cooling?).

Figure 5.3: Distribution of seasonal energy consumption for Heat Pumps for all houses for 2015

Energy consumption of Lighting is particularly apparent in spring, autumn, and winter as presented in Figure 5.4. Less energy consumption is identified in summer.

Figure 5.4: Distribition of seasonal energy consumption for Lighting for all houses for 2015

For ovens, there is less seasonal variation in seasonal energy consumption as shown in Figure 5.4. Furthermore, energy consumption in summer is less than in other seasons.

Figure 5.5: Distribution of seasonal energy consumption for Ovens for all houses for 2015

For Others, there is a lot of seasonal variation in seasonal energy consumption as shown in Figure 5.6. As this circuit contains appliances not further specified it is difficult to identify the appliance causing this energy consumption, particularly in summer. Therefore, further research is necessary.

Figure 5.6: Distribution of seasonal energy consumption for Others for all houses for 2015

6 Load Factor

## Warning in `[.data.table`(consloadEECADT, , `:=`(averagecontri,
## ConsLoadFactorSupplyDT$averageContri)): Supplied 20 items to be assigned
## to 125 items of column 'averagecontri' (recycled leaving remainder of 5
## items).

The Load Factor (LF) is defined as the ratio of average demand (W) in any given half-hour? to peak demand (W). The LF varies between 0 and 1 and provides a measure of how much the load contributes to peak. If the LF for a particular load is 1 then the load is flat. If it is less than one it shows that the load disproportionately contributes to the peak. In this section we define peak demand to be the maximum demand between 17:00-21:00 in winter (see first definition of peak demand).

Figure 6.1 shows the Load Factor (LF) for each identifiable load averaged over all houses in the sample. Based on this definition power was calculated as an average over all households. This calculation builds the average seasonal demand by circuit, linkID, and season and then averages this over the houses. In a second step, we utilise the identified maximum demand used for the first definition of peak demand to estimate the LF. Results show that the LF for Lighting (0.53) is the highest followed by Heat Pump (0.47) and Hot Water (0.25). Please note that these numbers represent averages over all households, dates, and times for 2015.

The full data table containing LFs (if available) for each house is saved as Extracted load factors for all houses for 2015 in winter between 17_21_00.csv and supplied with the report.

Figure 6.1: Conservation Load Factor by circuit for peak demand (17:00-21:00) in winter 2015
